{“questionId”: “cea66aee-3a10-4bb9-b653-46ec49321824_16”, “correctAnswer”: “D”, “section”: “Reading and Writing”, “steps”: [{“title”: “Map the series structure”, “content”: “The sentence reads: &quot;registering ______ and 16&deg;C at 5:00 p.m.&quot; The blank must fill in two temperature-time pairs that form a series with the final item. In a three-item series joined by &quot;and,&quot; standard comma rules require a comma after each item except the last &mdash; so the blank needs an internal comma between the two new items and a trailing comma before &quot;and.&quot;”}, {“title”: “Test each choice”, “content”: “<ul><li><strong>Choice A &mdash; '15.4&deg;C at 1:00 a.m. 18.6&deg;C at 11:30 a.m.'</strong>: no comma separating the two pairs and no trailing comma &mdash; the two items run together and the series is unpunctuated. &#10007;</li><li><strong>Choice B &mdash; '15.4&deg;C at 1:00 a.m. 18.6&deg;C at 11:30 a.m.,'</strong>: trailing comma present but still no comma between the two temperature-time pairs &mdash; they remain fused. &#10007;</li><li><strong>Choice C &mdash; '15.4&deg;C, at 1:00 a.m. 18.6&deg;C, at 11:30 a.m.'</strong>: commas are placed between each temperature and its own time, splitting inseparable units &mdash; breaks the intended pairing. &#10007;</li><li><strong>Choice D &mdash; '15.4&deg;C at 1:00 a.m., 18.6&deg;C at 11:30 a.m.,'</strong>: comma correctly separates the two pairs, and the trailing comma slots the whole group into the series before &quot;and 16&deg;C at 5:00 p.m.&quot; &#10003;</li></ul>That matches choice D &mdash; <strong>D</strong> is correct.”}]}